Sub-Saharan African Stocks Report: KenolKobil, Sasini Are Active

-- B y   S t e p h e n   G u n n i o n
-- 
2011-09-21T15:04:59Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-21/sub-saharan-african-stocks-report-kenolkobil-sasini-are-active.html
Kenya ’s All-Share Index declined
for a third day, dropping 0.7 percent to 60.7 by the 3 p.m.
close in Nairobi, the capital.  The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index declined less
than 0.1 percent to 20,868.1 by the 2:30 p.m. close in Lagos,
according to a statement on the bourse’s website.  Namibia ’s
FTSE/ Namibia Overall Index (FTN098)  dropped less than 0.1 percent to
800.51 by 4 p.m. in Windhoek. In Mauritius, the SEMDEX Index
added less than 0.1 percent to 1,892.43 by the 1:30 p.m. close
in  Port Louis . The Ghana Stock Exchange was closed for a public
holiday.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  British American Investment Co. (BRIT KN), a Kenyan
financial-services company, rose to the highest in a week,
gaining 20 cents, or 3.5 percent, to 5.95 shillings. The
company’s price-earnings ratio fell to a level matching its
peers, attracting investors, said Victor Odendo, an investment
manager at Nairobi-based CIC Asset Management Ltd.  KenolKobil Ltd. (KNOC KN), a fuel retailer with operations
in nine African countries, declined for the first day in eight,
dropping 10 cents, or 1 percent, to 10.3 shillings. Oil fell in
 New York  as investors bet that fuel demand in the U.S. is waning
as stockpiles rise, while supplies from the Middle East and
Africa grow.  Sasini Ltd. (STCL)  , a Kenyan coffee grower, declined for
the first day in seven, slipping 45 cents, or 3.3 percent, to
13.3 shillings. Kenya’s benchmark coffee grade retreated 7.3
percent at an auction yesterday as bean supplies rose and as
quality declined, the Nairobi Coffee Exchange said. The average
price for all coffee sold fell 6.2 percent to $327.91 a bag from
the previous sale.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Stephen Gunnion in Johannesburg at 
